{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-section-js","path":"/section/structures-and-architecture","result":{"data":{"section":{"name":"1.  Structures and Architecture","id":"-3d1398ca-ad1a-5b7a-a62d-b27e5b2ffc1b","_rawContent":[{"_key":"a28b850a29a4","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"bbaef6f8a8f1","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Around 1847 and at the age of 50, William “Extra Billy” Smith (1797-1887) purchased a house with land just off Culpeper Street on the south side of Warrenton, Virginia. He set about greatly enlarging the house which he named Monte Rosa. It would later be renamed Neptune Lodge by James Kerfoot Maddux (1853-1930) who purchased the property in September, 1895. Maddux in his own right was also a prominent member of the Warrenton community. Mr. Maddux renamed the property in honor of one of his racehorses. The original property was located in the southern portion of the Town of Warrenton, with parts of it extending outside of the town’s limits. It included the Governor’s mansion, stables, an assortment of other farm related structures and approximately 220 acres of fields and woods. Today the property is in the heart of the Historic district of Warrenton and includes approximately seven acres of land consisting of the Governor’s mansion, stables, Extra Billy’s “office building”."}],"markDefs":[],"style":"floatLeft"},{"_key":"1dfcee458fe2","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"1fedc5290b3a0","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Monte Rosa is a notable historic home for multiple reasons:"}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"fa92abb5d803","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"6ac93333c377","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"It was built by a prominent attorney, a member of the House of Representatives and the two time and Civil War Governor of Virginia;"}],"level":1,"listItem":"bullet","markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"6a8a7cdf1605","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"43b3a462496f0","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"The house was originally built in an architecturally significant Italianate style and later converted to a Colonial style; while the large brick stables were and remain in the Italianate style’;"}],"level":1,"listItem":"bullet","markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"fa53a5365412","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"0b03b28e36b60","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"The property was used to operate US mail routes critical to a growing nation;"}],"level":1,"listItem":"bullet","markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"039a8427ec58","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"69bfc9943b060","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"The property hosted and served as a command center by both Union and Confederate forces throughout the Civil War;"}],"level":1,"listItem":"bullet","markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"4b55347f4958","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"25f7ede63c520","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"William “Extra Billy” Smith was a prominent Virginian and national figure and notable dignitaries of his time visited and worked from the property."}],"level":1,"listItem":"bullet","markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"2c7798f42b2e","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"65df554134520","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"The Town of Warrenton was incorporated on January 5, 1810 and named for General Joseph Warren, a Revolutionary War hero. After a land grant from Richard Henry Lee, it became the Fauquier County seat. The original house was constructed about 1847–1848 on the south side of Warrenton. It is three story, brick and stucco structure and approximately 5,848 sq. ft. The house has a slate gable roof and side-passage floor plan. In the back of the main structure is a copper roof covered promenade that leads to a two-story brick smoke house. The house has sustained several periods of alteration. It was originally built in the Italianate architectural style with a sweeping front steps leading to the front door on the second floor. Today it now manifests the proportions and details of the Colonial Revival style with the main entrance now being on the ground level. Also on the property is an architecturally significant Italianate style brick stable (c. 1847) also built by Extra Billy to house his U.S. postal service; the aforementioned two-story brick smokehouse; and a two-story single-pile dwelling that dates from the late-19th century and is known as Extra Billy’s Office."}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"faca67e56e71","_type":"image","asset":{"_id":"image-1811fff8457901e0893db48524a05be8763a5fcb-372x231-jpg","_type":"sanity.imageAsset","_rev":"MZ5ftYniGNKTXADXt8RspD","_createdAt":"2020-11-26T07:24:45Z","_updatedAt":"2020-11-26T07:24:45Z","assetId":"1811fff8457901e0893db48524a05be8763a5fcb","extension":"jpg","metadata":{"_type":"sanity.imageMetadata","dimensions":{"_type":"sanity.imageDimensions","aspectRatio":1.6103896103896105,"height":231,"width":372},"hasAlpha":false,"isOpaque":true,"lqip":"data:image/jpeg;base64,","palette":{"_type":"sanity.imagePalette","darkMuted":{"_type":"sanity.imagePaletteSwatch","background":"#444444","foreground":"#fff","population":4.4,"title":"#fff"},"darkVibrant":{"_type":"sanity.imagePaletteSwatch","background":"#424242","foreground":"#fff","population":0,"title":"#fff"},"dominant":{"_type":"sanity.imagePaletteSwatch","background":"#878787","foreground":"#fff","population":4.99,"title":"#fff"},"lightMuted":{"_type":"sanity.imagePaletteSwatch","background":"#bcbcbc","foreground":"#000","population":1.9,"title":"#fff"},"lightVibrant":{"_type":"sanity.imagePaletteSwatch","background":"#bcbcbc","foreground":"#000","population":0,"title":"#fff"},"muted":{"_type":"sanity.imagePaletteSwatch","background":"#878787","foreground":"#fff","population":4.99,"title":"#fff"},"vibrant":{"_type":"sanity.imagePaletteSwatch","background":"#7f7f7f","foreground":"#fff","population":0,"title":"#fff"}}},"mimeType":"image/jpeg","originalFilename":"monterosa-1.jpg","path":"images/c2zb4c1w/production/1811fff8457901e0893db48524a05be8763a5fcb-372x231.jpg","sha1hash":"1811fff8457901e0893db48524a05be8763a5fcb","size":42075,"uploadId":"1JcvI9NUW26Scx5nEBjOvmi0MKEy8Mct","url":"https://cdn.sanity.io/images/c2zb4c1w/production/1811fff8457901e0893db48524a05be8763a5fcb-372x231.jpg","id":"image-1811fff8457901e0893db48524a05be8763a5fcb-372x231-jpg","parent":null,"children":["e3659de3-457f-5294-8ad8-5f3fe4f11779"],"internal":{"type":"SanityImageAsset","contentDigest":"90f30a628162d2e7c7f19e3852977433","counter":38,"owner":"gatsby-source-sanity"}}},{"_key":"037792202da7","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"0971e9723035","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":""}],"markDefs":[{"_key":"ea83e7ac6696","_type":"image"},{"_key":"88a214dd4fe1","_type":"image"},{"_key":"293bca31e807","_type":"image"},{"_key":"17bb52045f4e","_type":"image"}],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"dd1253c90cd9","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"9663600006a8","_type":"span","marks":["9dc80093c442"],"text":"The original house was built in the Italianate style in the 1840s, as shown (to the left) in a promotional brochure produced for the failed South Warrenton development project. The original structure had a large ornate staircase that entered the house at the piano noble level (second floor). The Smith Mansion became well known for stylish entertaining as both Elizabeth and William Smith were heralded as being excellent hosts. Many notable and prominent figures in his business and political world came to Monte Rosa."}],"markDefs":[{"_key":"9dc80093c442","_type":"image","asset":{"_id":"image-1811fff8457901e0893db48524a05be8763a5fcb-372x231-jpg","_type":"sanity.imageAsset","_rev":"MZ5ftYniGNKTXADXt8RspD","_createdAt":"2020-11-26T07:24:45Z","_updatedAt":"2020-11-26T07:24:45Z","assetId":"1811fff8457901e0893db48524a05be8763a5fcb","extension":"jpg","metadata":{"_type":"sanity.imageMetadata","dimensions":{"_type":"sanity.imageDimensions","aspectRatio":1.6103896103896105,"height":231,"width":372},"hasAlpha":false,"isOpaque":true,"lqip":"data:image/jpeg;base64,","palette":{"_type":"sanity.imagePalette","darkMuted":{"_type":"sanity.imagePaletteSwatch","background":"#444444","foreground":"#fff","population":4.4,"title":"#fff"},"darkVibrant":{"_type":"sanity.imagePaletteSwatch","background":"#424242","foreground":"#fff","population":0,"title":"#fff"},"dominant":{"_type":"sanity.imagePaletteSwatch","background":"#878787","foreground":"#fff","population":4.99,"title":"#fff"},"lightMuted":{"_type":"sanity.imagePaletteSwatch","background":"#bcbcbc","foreground":"#000","population":1.9,"title":"#fff"},"lightVibrant":{"_type":"sanity.imagePaletteSwatch","background":"#bcbcbc","foreground":"#000","population":0,"title":"#fff"},"muted":{"_type":"sanity.imagePaletteSwatch","background":"#878787","foreground":"#fff","population":4.99,"title":"#fff"},"vibrant":{"_type":"sanity.imagePaletteSwatch","background":"#7f7f7f","foreground":"#fff","population":0,"title":"#fff"}}},"mimeType":"image/jpeg","originalFilename":"monterosa-1.jpg","path":"images/c2zb4c1w/production/1811fff8457901e0893db48524a05be8763a5fcb-372x231.jpg","sha1hash":"1811fff8457901e0893db48524a05be8763a5fcb","size":42075,"uploadId":"1JcvI9NUW26Scx5nEBjOvmi0MKEy8Mct","url":"https://cdn.sanity.io/images/c2zb4c1w/production/1811fff8457901e0893db48524a05be8763a5fcb-372x231.jpg","id":"image-1811fff8457901e0893db48524a05be8763a5fcb-372x231-jpg","parent":null,"children":["e3659de3-457f-5294-8ad8-5f3fe4f11779"],"internal":{"type":"SanityImageAsset","contentDigest":"90f30a628162d2e7c7f19e3852977433","counter":38,"owner":"gatsby-source-sanity"}}}],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"fbed4d55f983","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"0ea14814c82e","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":""}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"cb78be7217b8","_type":"image","asset":{"_id":"image-5672738ea6cd9c6827dd084009b19e9bcf92a6d4-614x389-png","_type":"sanity.imageAsset","_rev":"slFLVCrL7OR5GTaBJkydOJ","_createdAt":"2020-11-26T07:27:59Z","_updatedAt":"2020-11-26T07:27:59Z","assetId":"5672738ea